00:15:41.860 --> 00:15:45.700
'There's a man who owns a jackass,

00:15:45.700 --> 00:15:49.180
and it's worth $50,
so the man can vote.

00:15:49.180 --> 00:15:51.550
Then the jackass dies.

00:15:51.550 --> 00:15:52.850
The man is older.

00:15:52.850 --> 00:15:55.150
He understands more
about government,

00:15:55.150 --> 00:15:57.790
but the jackass is still dead.

00:15:57.790 --> 00:15:59.330
So the man cannot vote.

00:15:59.330 --> 00:16:02.950
So therefore,' he asked, 'who
really has the right to vote?

00:16:02.950 --> 00:16:05.640
The man or the jackass.'

00:16:05.640 --> 00:16:08.300
This seemed pretty
persuasive in Pennsylvania

00:16:08.300 --> 00:16:11.570 position:56%
and they created the most democratic
constitution the world had

00:16:11.570 --> 00:16:13.070
ever seen.

00:16:13.070 --> 00:16:18.160
Up in Massachusetts, John Adams
reflected the other strain.

00:16:18.160 --> 00:16:20.850
He was aghast at this notion
of expanding the right to vote,

00:16:20.850 --> 00:16:22.810
of expanding American democracy.

00:16:22.810 --> 00:16:25.310
He wrote their Constitution, he
was urged to do the same thing,

00:16:25.310 --> 00:16:27.590
to end the property requirement.

00:16:27.590 --> 00:16:32.440
And he wrote, he said,
'If you do that, he said,

00:16:32.440 --> 00:16:35.720 position:56%
women will demand the right to vote.

00:16:35.720 --> 00:16:39.550 position:56%
Lads of 18 will think their
interests insufficiently attended to

00:16:39.550 --> 00:16:41.510
and they will demand
the right to vote.

00:16:41.510 --> 00:16:43.500
And men,' he said, '
who have not a farthing

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:46.550
to their name will think
themselves worthy of an equal voice

00:16:46.550 --> 00:16:49.220
in government and then will
demand the right to vote.'

00:16:49.220 --> 00:16:52.390
Adam said, 'there will
be no end of it.'

00:16:52.390 --> 00:16:53.690
And that's basically the book.

00:16:53.690 --> 00:16:56.520
That's basically the
story of what happened

00:16:56.520 --> 00:16:59.830
over the next 2.5 centuries.

00:16:59.830 --> 00:17:03.550
The idea that government rested
on the consent of the governed,

00:17:03.550 --> 00:17:04.850
and that the vote was the center

00:17:04.850 --> 00:17:07.410
of that consent took
on a life of its own.

00:17:07.410 --> 00:17:12.410
And it's worth noting in
this wonderful building,

00:17:12.410 --> 00:17:14.230
named after James Madison.

00:17:14.230 --> 00:17:20.330
As you know, Madison's notes
are our principle basis

00:17:20.330 --> 00:17:22.930
for understanding what
the conversations were

00:17:22.930 --> 00:17:24.510
at the constitutional convention.

00:17:24.510 --> 00:17:27.010
And the Constitution
does not originally refer

00:17:27.010 --> 00:17:28.400
to a right to a right to vote.

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:30.850
There was even a move to put
that property requirement

00:17:30.850 --> 00:17:34.730
into the Constitution,
which Madison shrugged off.

00:17:34.730 --> 00:17:38.630 position:56%
He didn't think it was such a bad
idea, but he did it was a good idea.

00:17:38.630 --> 00:17:43.260
And Franklin actually
blocked it with his prestige.

00:17:43.260 --> 00:17:45.960
We only know those notes

00:17:45.960 --> 00:17:48.800
because they were released
many decades later.

00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:53.350
But when the doors opened
up and it came time to fight

00:17:53.350 --> 00:17:55.410
for the ratification
of the Constitution,

00:17:55.410 --> 00:18:00.000
in that very controversial
debate where the antifederalists,

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.570
as they were called,
made a very strong case

00:18:03.570 --> 00:18:05.270
against the Constitution.

00:18:05.270 --> 00:18:07.670
One of the issues was this question

00:18:07.670 --> 00:18:11.050
of whether it was a counter
revolution, whether it was elitist,

00:18:11.050 --> 00:18:15.130
whether the ordinary people
would be cut out, and Madison

00:18:15.130 --> 00:18:18.300
and the other founders, even the
ones who didn't believe it went

00:18:18.300 --> 00:18:20.830
to the country and said no
this is about democracy.

00:18:20.830 --> 00:18:23.900
In Federalist 57, Madison
asked the question.

00:18:23.900 --> 00:18:27.040
He said, 'Who are to be the
electors of the new government?

00:18:27.040 --> 00:18:29.480
Not the rich more than the poor.

00:18:29.480 --> 00:18:32.160
Not the learned more
than the ignorant.

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:35.790
Not the haughty heirs of famous
names more than the humble sons

00:18:35.790 --> 00:18:38.960
of obscurity and unpropitious
fortune.

00:18:38.960 --> 00:18:42.900
The great body of the people
are to be the electors."

00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:48.730 position:56%
That's as compelling a definition of
democracy as we could find even now.

00:18:48.730 --> 00:18:51.220
And again, that took
on a life of its own.

00:18:51.220 --> 00:18:57.850
In the 1820s and the 1830s, was
the first great breakthrough

00:18:57.850 --> 00:18:59.540
for this expanded right to vote.

00:18:59.540 --> 00:19:05.330 position:56%
And in the modern political context,
it's worth noting it was won

00:19:05.330 --> 00:19:09.830
by angry, white, working-class
men of the time.

00:19:09.830 --> 00:19:12.410
The period of Jacksonian Democracy.

00:19:12.410 --> 00:19:14.400
When states all across
the country ended

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:17.410
that property for white
men in voting.

00:19:17.410 --> 00:19:20.300
And one of the interesting
and for me,

00:19:20.300 --> 00:19:24.580
slightly unexpected storylines
throughout all of this,

00:19:24.580 --> 00:19:27.230
is that that victory for
voting rights was not won

00:19:27.230 --> 00:19:32.240
by voting rights groups, or a
lawsuit, or citizen activists.

00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:36.430
It was waged and won by
political parties, by politicians,

00:19:36.430 --> 00:19:38.900
by cynical insiders often.

00:19:38.900 --> 00:19:44.040
One of the great leaders in
that fight was Martin Van Buren,

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:48.390
who was the governor of New
York and then President.

00:19:48.390 --> 00:19:54.070
And Van Buren helped to found the
world's first mass political party,

00:19:54.070 --> 00:19:57.090
the Democratic Party,
as we now call it.

00:19:57.090 --> 00:19:58.830 position:56%
Around this issue of wider suffrage.

00:19:58.830 --> 00:20:01.040
And he was no firebrand.

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:06.090
There's a story from the time that
the Albany was notoriously corrupt,

00:20:06.090 --> 00:20:09.640
even then as a state capital, and
one state senator bet another.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:11.730
He said I bet you I
can get Van Buren

00:20:11.730 --> 00:20:14.260
to give a straight answer
to a simple question.

00:20:14.260 --> 00:20:15.680
And the other guy took the bet.

00:20:15.680 --> 00:20:19.130
And he went up to Van Buren and
said, Mr. Van Buren, tell me,

00:20:19.130 --> 00:20:22.270
is it true that the
sun rises in the east?

00:20:22.270 --> 00:20:27.410
And Van Buren said well, seeing
as how I never wake up that early,

00:20:27.410 --> 00:20:29.770
I cannot speak to that
from personal experience,

00:20:29.770 --> 00:20:32.450
so I don't know the answer to that.

00:20:32.450 --> 00:20:35.540
He led the fight to
expand voting rights.

00:20:35.540 --> 00:20:42.350
And this role of insiders, the role
politicians and political parties,

00:20:42.350 --> 00:20:46.260
is a significant storyline
throughout this

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:49.720
that recurs and often surprises.

00:20:49.720 --> 00:20:52.960
The next great breakthrough
of course,

00:20:52.960 --> 00:20:56.420
albeit one that was
tragically cut short,

00:20:56.420 --> 00:20:59.010 position:56%
came during and after the Civil War.

00:20:59.010 --> 00:21:05.280
Because the expansion of the
vote to working-class white men,

00:21:05.280 --> 00:21:07.170
the idea that we were democracy.

00:21:07.170 --> 00:21:10.690 position:56%
The almost faddish devotion to
political participation that you saw

00:21:10.690 --> 00:21:14.390
around the country,
again set up the demand

00:21:14.390 --> 00:21:16.370
for the next great breakthrough.

00:21:16.370 --> 00:21:20.000
At the end of the Civil War, as the
book describes, Frederick Douglass

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:23.800 position:56%
and the other abolitionists realized
that the next great fight was

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:26.300
to enfranchise the former slaves.

00:21:26.300 --> 00:21:29.180
To extend the right
to vote to black men.

00:21:29.180 --> 00:21:35.080
And Lincoln, Abraham Lincoln was
opposed to extending the right

00:21:35.080 --> 00:21:37.620
to vote to the former slaves.

00:21:37.620 --> 00:21:38.950
He was ardently against it.

00:21:38.950 --> 00:21:40.920
He campaigned against it.

00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:45.760
But on this, as on so many other
issues, the war changed Lincoln.

00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:52.770
By the end of the war, 1 out of
10 Union soldiers was a black man.

00:21:52.770 --> 00:21:56.060
When Lincoln, just
a few hundred yards

00:21:56.060 --> 00:21:59.820
from here gave his famous
second inaugural address,

00:21:59.820 --> 00:22:03.930
back when the inaugurals were
on this side of the capital,

00:22:03.930 --> 00:22:06.090
half the audience were
African-American men

00:22:06.090 --> 00:22:11.160
and women, many of them in uniform.

00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:16.300
And 3 days after Appomattox,
3 days after the surrender

00:22:16.300 --> 00:22:21.190
by Robert E. Lee, Lincoln
gave his first major speech

00:22:21.190 --> 00:22:22.490
on reconstruction.

00:22:22.490 --> 00:22:25.970
On what he wanted to have
happen after the Civil War.

00:22:25.970 --> 00:22:28.560
It was a long speech and he gave
it to from the second floor window

00:22:28.560 --> 00:22:30.160
of the White House by candlelight.

00:22:30.160 --> 00:22:35.250
And in the middle of the speech he
said, 'Now I've been criticized,

00:22:35.250 --> 00:22:36.750
because his original plans

00:22:36.750 --> 00:22:39.250
for reconstruction did
not extend voting rights.

00:22:39.250 --> 00:22:45.050 position:56%
And he said, 'I've been criticized
for not extending the right to vote.

00:22:45.050 --> 00:22:47.550 position:56%
And I now agree with that criticism.

00:22:47.550 --> 00:22:50.830
In fact, I think that there should
be the right to vote for those

00:22:50.830 --> 00:22:53.060
who have served in the military,
for those who are intelligent.'

00:22:53.060 --> 00:22:54.470
He went through some categories.

00:22:54.470 --> 00:22:56.340
And actually in the cabinet
meeting a few days later,

00:22:56.340 --> 00:23:00.600
he made clear to his cabinet that
he was likely to go the whole way.

00:23:00.600 --> 00:23:04.710
At least one member of the
audience, historians tell us,

00:23:04.710 --> 00:23:07.810
caught the significance
of what Lincoln said.

00:23:07.810 --> 00:23:10.320
John Wilkes Booth was there.

00:23:10.320 --> 00:23:15.020
And when Lincoln said this, Booth
gasped that means citizenship.

00:23:15.020 --> 00:23:18.590
That is the last speech
he will ever give.

00:23:18.590 --> 00:23:21.280
And he in fact tried to
get the guy at that moment

00:23:21.280 --> 00:23:23.480
to shoot Lincoln on the spot.

00:23:23.480 --> 00:23:24.780
The guy standing next to him.

00:23:24.780 --> 00:23:27.580
And when he wouldn't
do it, Booth said,

00:23:27.580 --> 00:23:29.400
'Well then by God I
will put him through.

00:23:29.400 --> 00:23:33.240
And two days later, went to
Ford's Theater and did that.

00:23:33.240 --> 00:23:37.630
This was the case that,
I'm not meaning to imply

00:23:37.630 --> 00:23:41.920
that Booth was a big
Lincoln fan other than that.

00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:46.260 position:56%
His previous idea had been to you
know kidnap him and bring him south.

00:23:46.260 --> 00:23:50.240
But the spark for the
assassination, we are told was

00:23:50.240 --> 00:23:54.340
in fact Lincoln's conversion
to the cause of voting rights.

00:23:54.340 --> 00:23:58.640
And this was, as it turns out
one of the great central fights.

00:23:58.640 --> 00:24:02.010
One of the great central
issues in reconstruction.

00:24:02.010 --> 00:24:06.660
And again, one where
partisanship plays a significant,

00:24:06.660 --> 00:24:09.830
positive role in expanding
the right to vote.

00:24:09.830 --> 00:24:12.230
This time it was the
Republican Party,

00:24:12.230 --> 00:24:14.990
which pushed through the 15th
amendment to the Constitution,

00:24:14.990 --> 00:24:17.270
which prohibited discrimination.

00:24:17.270 --> 00:24:23.090
Which said the right to vote could
not be abridged because of race.

00:24:23.090 --> 00:24:27.310
And it's important to note, as I
said, this is a partisan issue.

00:24:27.310 --> 00:24:30.300
The identity of which party is
pushing for greater voting rights,

00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:34.010
and which party is pushing against
voting rights, often changes.

00:24:34.010 --> 00:24:35.310
Often switches.

00:24:35.310 --> 00:24:36.610
It's not always one
party or another.

00:24:36.610 --> 00:24:37.910 position:56%
In this case it was the republicans.

00:24:37.910 --> 00:24:41.910
They did this out of a mix of
idealism and political calculus,

00:24:41.910 --> 00:24:46.530
to help win the black
vote in the border states.

00:24:46.530 --> 00:24:54.270
But, it's also worth noting that, I
mentioned that the phrase the right

00:24:54.270 --> 00:24:57.240
to vote, the notion of a right to
vote was not in the Constitution.

00:24:57.240 --> 00:24:58.840
And you'll hear people
say that all the time.

00:24:58.840 --> 00:25:00.140
That it's not in the Constitution.

00:25:00.140 --> 00:25:01.440
There's no right to vote.

00:25:01.440 --> 00:25:03.730
Well it wasn't in the
original Constitution.

00:25:03.730 --> 00:25:05.470
But starting with the
15th amendment,

00:25:05.470 --> 00:25:07.680
and actually the 14th
amendment before that.

00:25:07.680 --> 00:25:08.980
It has been added

00:25:08.980 --> 00:25:11.850
to the Constitution 5
separate times, explicitly.

00:25:11.850 --> 00:25:13.510
There is a right to vote
in the Constitution.

00:25:13.510 --> 00:25:16.740
It's in there more than
just about any other topic.

00:25:16.740 --> 00:25:19.400
But it was added after
the original Constitution.

00:25:19.400 --> 00:25:21.730
And this was one of the
most significant times.

00:25:21.730 --> 00:25:24.890
And what many Americans for
a long time did not realize,

00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:29.360
and we now all understand is that
there was a flowering of democracy

00:25:29.360 --> 00:25:32.030
in the south after
the 15th amendment.

00:25:32.030 --> 00:25:36.900
Voter participation rates among
African-American men reached 90%.

00:25:36.900 --> 00:25:41.500
Hundreds were elected to state
legislatures, to Congress,

00:25:41.500 --> 00:25:44.470
to governorships, even
to the U.S. Senate.

00:25:44.470 --> 00:25:48.920
And then as we know, it was
cruelly, effectively revoked.

00:25:48.920 --> 00:25:50.950
First, by terrorism.

00:25:50.950 --> 00:25:53.990
By the Ku Klux Klan and
other paramilitary groups,

00:25:53.990 --> 00:25:55.460
which were serving in effect

00:25:55.460 --> 00:25:59.340
as a military wing of
the Democratic Party.

00:25:59.340 --> 00:26:01.980
This is not, we all
understand the perils

00:26:01.980 --> 00:26:03.460
of living in an age of terrorism.

00:26:03.460 --> 00:26:05.970
This was, we are not
living in either the first,

00:26:05.970 --> 00:26:08.640
or the greatest age of
terrorism in the United States.

00:26:08.640 --> 00:26:10.740
That was after the Civil War.

00:26:10.740 --> 00:26:14.020
The violence drove many
people away from the polls.

00:26:14.020 --> 00:26:19.160
And then cowardice, and
a cynical deal struck

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:22.960
out to settle the 1876
presidential election

00:26:22.960 --> 00:26:26.490
that saw the troops
withdrawn from the south.

00:26:26.490 --> 00:26:30.460
And effectively ended
for a century or so,

00:26:30.460 --> 00:26:33.500
the national government's effort
to protect the right to vote

00:26:33.500 --> 00:26:36.490
for the former slaves
and their descendants.

00:26:36.490 --> 00:26:38.160
And one of things that
was interesting is

00:26:38.160 --> 00:26:40.090
that it didn't happen right away.

00:26:40.090 --> 00:26:44.270
Voter turnout rates among black
men was actually quite high

00:26:44.270 --> 00:26:46.540 position:56%
in the south for decades after that.

00:26:46.540 --> 00:26:50.800
It wasn't until the Jim Crow
Constitution of the 1890s,

00:26:50.800 --> 00:26:54.180
which formally, and creatively

00:26:54.180 --> 00:26:57.160
and systematically
disenfranchise black voters.

00:26:57.160 --> 00:27:00.620
That it was completely done.

00:27:00.620 --> 00:27:04.910
And as many of you know, that
central fact what was called

00:27:04.910 --> 00:27:06.880
in those days the solid south.

00:27:06.880 --> 00:27:10.110
The all-white Democratic
Party south,

00:27:10.110 --> 00:27:12.910
with very low voter
participation rates

00:27:12.910 --> 00:27:16.400
of any kind was the
central political fact

00:27:16.400 --> 00:27:18.800
in American government
for decades and decades.

00:27:18.800 --> 00:27:21.900
Well into the 20th
century, into my lifetime.

00:27:21.900 --> 00:27:25.420
What a lot of people don't
know, is that during this period

00:27:25.420 --> 00:27:30.490
in the late 19th century, something
similar happened in the north,

00:27:30.490 --> 00:27:32.960
not as bad, but something similar.

00:27:32.960 --> 00:27:38.080
The cities of the North during this
time were filled with immigrants.

00:27:38.080 --> 00:27:40.410 position:56%
They weren't immigrants from Mexico.

00:27:40.410 --> 00:27:44.490
They were from Ireland, and
Italy, and Russia, and Poland,

00:27:44.490 --> 00:27:46.780
and other European countries.

00:27:46.780 --> 00:27:50.070
And a lot of the established
institutions,

00:27:50.070 --> 00:27:54.560
a lot of the blue bloods of
the time reacted with language

00:27:54.560 --> 00:27:59.200
that would be very
familiar to us today.

00:27:59.200 --> 00:28:02.630
And in fact, many of them
decided that this idea

00:28:02.630 --> 00:28:06.140
of universal voting rights wasn't
such a good idea after all.

00:28:06.140 --> 00:28:11.750 position:56%
John Adams' great grandson said
that if you have universal suffrage,

00:28:11.750 --> 00:28:16.920
you will have government of
corruption and vice dominated,

00:28:16.920 --> 00:28:20.510
as he said by the Celtic
proletariat in the North,

00:28:20.510 --> 00:28:22.510
the African proletariat
in the South,

00:28:22.510 --> 00:28:24.720 position:56%
the Chinese proletariat in the West.

00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:28.060
So it turned out that voting rights
wasn't such a good idea after all.

00:28:28.060 --> 00:28:32.870
Two of my favorite
surprises during that period,

00:28:32.870 --> 00:28:35.770
one of the great leaders of
the opposition to the right

00:28:35.770 --> 00:28:39.980
to vote was E.L. Godkin, who
founded the "Nation Magazine"

00:28:39.980 --> 00:28:43.970
and Walt Whitman, wrote ardently
against democracy at this point,

00:28:43.970 --> 00:28:47.110
and against the right to
vote for the same reasons.

00:28:47.110 --> 00:28:51.140
And what you saw throughout
the north were a series of laws

00:28:51.140 --> 00:28:52.700
and a series of practices.

00:28:52.700 --> 00:28:55.280
Some of them quite
defensible on their face,

00:28:55.280 --> 00:28:58.690
that effectively made it much
harder for working people,

00:28:58.690 --> 00:29:00.520
for non-English speakers,

00:29:00.520 --> 00:29:04.820
for non-educated people,
for poor people to vote.

00:29:04.820 --> 00:29:07.840 position:56%
Everything from voter
registration, which was a new thing,

00:29:07.840 --> 00:29:12.440
imposed in many places only in
democratic and Catholic big cities

00:29:12.440 --> 00:29:17.720
and not in republican and rural
areas out in the countryside.

00:29:17.720 --> 00:29:19.920
Even something like
the printed ballot

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:23.410
which means you have
to be able to read it.

00:29:23.410 --> 00:29:27.510
Or the secret ballot, which
meant that similarly that you had

00:29:27.510 --> 00:29:30.180
to process who you were
voting for on your own.

00:29:30.180 --> 00:29:33.980
Things that we obviously think are
important parts of what it means

00:29:33.980 --> 00:29:36.180 position:56%
to run a clean and honest democracy.

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:40.480
Always these various things
made it harder, and harder,

00:29:40.480 --> 00:29:45.680
and harder the other
crackdowns on the often corrupt,

00:29:45.680 --> 00:29:49.070
but highly participatory
political parties of the time meant

00:29:49.070 --> 00:29:53.670
that voter turnout rates began to
really plummet in the late 1800s.

00:29:53.670 --> 00:29:58.080 position:56%
And then you added on top of that a
new factor, which began at that time

00:29:58.080 --> 00:30:00.190
and which of course we're living
with now, which is the role

00:30:00.190 --> 00:30:02.360
of big money in American politics.

00:30:02.360 --> 00:30:05.060
Which had not been a
factor until the late 1800s.

00:30:05.060 --> 00:30:10.520
But now with the tremendous
inequality of that Gilded Age time,

00:30:10.520 --> 00:30:14.920
the campaign money from the robber
barons began to dominate politics

00:30:14.920 --> 00:30:18.700
at the very moment that the
vote was being pushed back.

00:30:18.700 --> 00:30:23.440
So in many ways, American democracy
slid backwards in the late 1800s.

00:30:23.440 --> 00:30:25.680
And it's an important lesson.

00:30:25.680 --> 00:30:29.330
Because we think of the
beginning, where we were,

00:30:29.330 --> 00:30:31.920 position:56%
had a kernel of the democratic idea,

00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:33.880
but that we've expanded
it over time.

00:30:33.880 --> 00:30:37.640
And that's true and it's
true as Dr. King said talking

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:41.310
about voting rights that the
moral arc of the universe is long,

00:30:41.310 --> 00:30:43.050
but it bends toward justice.

00:30:43.050 --> 00:30:46.070
But it sometimes goes backwards.

00:30:46.070 --> 00:30:47.950 position:56%
Then what happened after that period

00:30:47.950 --> 00:30:51.380
in the late 19th century is
something else that also happens

00:30:51.380 --> 00:30:55.220
with some recurring frequency,
which is there was a response.

00:30:55.220 --> 00:30:58.570
There was a period of
reform and renewal.

00:30:58.570 --> 00:31:01.340
Very significantly in
response to what had happened.

00:31:01.340 --> 00:31:04.010
Now we know it of course,
as the Progressive Era.

00:31:04.010 --> 00:31:06.060
And when we learn about the
Progressive Era and we think

00:31:06.060 --> 00:31:09.870
about it, it's certainly the
case that it was in a lot

00:31:09.870 --> 00:31:14.410 position:56%
of respects very similar to our time
in terms of the public's concerns.

00:31:14.410 --> 00:31:17.430
People were unsettled
by economic change.

00:31:17.430 --> 00:31:21.810
They were unsettled by the new
degree of inequality that had come

00:31:21.810 --> 00:31:23.870
into the American economy.

00:31:23.870 --> 00:31:27.290
They were unnerved by
demographic change, by immigration.

00:31:27.290 --> 00:31:29.970
They felt that the
political system was rigged.

00:31:29.970 --> 00:31:33.420 position:56%
They felt that government was not
functional, that it was not working,

00:31:33.420 --> 00:31:35.170
given the challenges of that time.

00:31:35.170 --> 00:31:38.540
And we think about the Progressive
Era as being when the beginnings

00:31:38.540 --> 00:31:40.470
of the modern governmental
system was built,

00:31:40.470 --> 00:31:43.420
you know food safety
regulation, or antitrust laws.

00:31:43.420 --> 00:31:46.430
And that's all true, but to
the Progressives of the time,

00:31:46.430 --> 00:31:50.140
they felt that restoring and
revitalizing the institutions

00:31:50.140 --> 00:31:54.500
of American democracy, and
expanding the vote were critical

00:31:54.500 --> 00:31:56.100
to their efforts.

00:31:56.100 --> 00:31:59.210
They passed the first
campaign finance laws,

00:31:59.210 --> 00:32:02.450
some of which were
affected by Citizens United.

00:32:02.450 --> 00:32:06.650
They passed the 17th
amendment to the Constitution,

00:32:06.650 --> 00:32:11.430
which to them was a central
campaign finance reform effort.

00:32:11.430 --> 00:32:14.600
That was the moment that gave
the right to vote to people

00:32:14.600 --> 00:32:19.730
for senators, previously it
had been state legislatures

00:32:19.730 --> 00:32:21.030
who elected senators.

00:32:21.030 --> 00:32:24.380
And they felt that the state
legislatures were corrupt

00:32:24.380 --> 00:32:27.460
and were dominated by big special
interests and that giving that vote

00:32:27.460 --> 00:32:29.750
to a much wider group
would change that.

00:32:29.750 --> 00:32:32.040
And by the way when you hear today,

00:32:32.040 --> 00:32:37.050
some people actually urge the
revocation of the 17th amendment.

00:32:37.050 --> 00:32:40.450
Saying that it was a power grab by
Washington imposed on the states.

00:32:40.450 --> 00:32:42.290
It's actually the other way around.

00:32:42.290 --> 00:32:44.460
The U.S. Senate was the
last place that wanted

00:32:44.460 --> 00:32:45.760
to do the 17th amendment.

00:32:45.760 --> 00:32:48.430
It was actually demanded
by the states and by people

00:32:48.430 --> 00:32:50.360
of the states at the time.

00:32:50.360 --> 00:32:55.400
And we know that they expanded
direct democracy, referenda,

00:32:55.400 --> 00:32:59.330
and a whole host of other ways
that this vote gained more power.

00:32:59.330 --> 00:33:04.240 position:56%
And they took the single, in numeric
terms, the single biggest step

00:33:04.240 --> 00:33:08.470
to expand the vote, which
is the 19th amendment,

00:33:08.470 --> 00:33:10.570
guaranteeing the right
to vote to women.

00:33:10.570 --> 00:33:12.900
And we sort of skip
over this one often

00:33:12.900 --> 00:33:14.490
in our thinking of
American democracy.

00:33:14.490 --> 00:33:15.880
We know it happened.

00:33:15.880 --> 00:33:20.430
But it turns out that the
fight for the vote for women,

00:33:20.430 --> 00:33:25.130
for that 19th amendment, was
every bit as fiercely contested,

00:33:25.130 --> 00:33:29.470
as dramatic, as any voting
rights fight before or since.

00:33:29.470 --> 00:33:32.510
And there are many stories that
we learned for the first time.

00:33:32.510 --> 00:33:37.980 position:56%
Those of us at the Brenna Center,
we work on this stuff day and night.

00:33:37.980 --> 00:33:41.080
You know, we know and
Secretary Clinton mentioned this

00:33:41.080 --> 00:33:43.850
in her speech the other
day that in 1848

00:33:43.850 --> 00:33:48.180
at Seneca Falls was the first time
that the demand for a right to vote

00:33:48.180 --> 00:33:51.870
for women was really put forward
by the Seneca Falls Declaration.

00:33:51.870 --> 00:33:55.500
The fact is not a whole lot
happened after that, for decades

00:33:55.500 --> 00:33:57.710
and decades not a whole
lot happened after that.

00:33:57.710 --> 00:34:04.280
And it was not until 1911, when a
small group of very young women,

00:34:04.280 --> 00:34:06.820
many of them had been in
graduate school in England,

00:34:06.820 --> 00:34:09.570
where they participated in
the suffrage movement there.

00:34:09.570 --> 00:34:14.860
Came back to the United States and
in the face of kind of eye rolling

00:34:14.860 --> 00:34:16.980
by their elders said
that they were going

00:34:16.980 --> 00:34:19.040
to try something really audacious.

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:22.220
There were going to actually try
to pass a constitutional amendment

00:34:22.220 --> 00:34:25.530
to give women the right to vote.

00:34:25.530 --> 00:34:30.900
Just 3 months later, the day before
his inauguration as president,

00:34:30.900 --> 00:34:35.030
Woodrow Wilson got off the
train a few blocks from here,

00:34:35.030 --> 00:34:39.060
and was expecting to be
greeted by a giant throng.

00:34:39.060 --> 00:34:41.480
And there was basically
nobody there.

00:34:41.480 --> 00:34:44.770
It was the Princeton Glee
Club and that was it.

00:34:44.770 --> 00:34:49.520
They belted out a song, and
"The New York Times" wrote,

00:34:49.520 --> 00:34:52.500
they made up in enthusiasm
what they lacked in numbers.

00:34:52.500 --> 00:34:56.190
They were very pro-democrat
even then.

00:34:56.190 --> 00:34:59.950
And finally Wilson's aide
said, where are all the people?

00:34:59.950 --> 00:35:03.850
And the hosts said with
sort of embarrassment, well,

00:35:03.850 --> 00:35:08.450 position:56%
they're actually all down
Pennsylvania Avenue where there was,

00:35:08.450 --> 00:35:11.840
for the very first time, a
march for women's suffrage

00:35:11.840 --> 00:35:14.810
down Pennsylvania Avenue the day
before the presidential inaugural,

00:35:14.810 --> 00:35:18.600
5000 women marching
for the right to vote.

00:35:18.600 --> 00:35:24.520
At the head of the parade was a
27-year-old woman on a white horse,

00:35:24.520 --> 00:35:28.860
named Inez Milholland,
dressed in the costume

00:35:28.860 --> 00:35:32.400
of a Greek goddess
carrying a banner,

00:35:32.400 --> 00:35:34.330
sort of a hallucinatory figuring.

00:35:34.330 --> 00:35:39.230
And we're especially fond of her,
because she was a recent graduate

00:35:39.230 --> 00:35:42.710
of NYU School of Law, where
the Brannan Center is.

00:35:42.710 --> 00:35:44.590
And 5000 women.

00:35:44.590 --> 00:35:48.000
And on either side a
hundred thousand men flanking

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:49.680
Pennsylvania Avenue.

00:35:49.680 --> 00:35:51.180
They were there for the inaugural.

00:35:51.180 --> 00:35:52.890
Many of them were drunk.

00:35:52.890 --> 00:35:55.550
And they started spitting
and throwing things.

00:35:55.550 --> 00:35:58.620
They broke through the lines
and assaulted the women.

00:35:58.620 --> 00:35:59.990
Beat them up.

00:35:59.990 --> 00:36:02.060
Sent 100 women to the hospital.

00:36:02.060 --> 00:36:04.540
They had to fight their way
down Pennsylvania Avenue

00:36:04.540 --> 00:36:07.770
to the Treasury Department,
where the march ended.

00:36:07.770 --> 00:36:09.940
And it was a very big deal.

00:36:09.940 --> 00:36:12.580
It was massively publicized.

00:36:12.580 --> 00:36:17.010
The publicity you know, overshadow
the inauguration in many ways.

00:36:17.010 --> 00:36:19.940
The police chief of
Washington DC had to resign.

00:36:19.940 --> 00:36:26.890
And public opinion swung in
support of voting rights for women.

00:36:26.890 --> 00:36:30.770
And when I learned this story,
I thought and perhaps some

00:36:30.770 --> 00:36:32.720
of you are having the same thought.

00:36:32.720 --> 00:36:35.440
That sounds just like Selma.

00:36:35.440 --> 00:36:42.030
That this public publicized
attack on nonviolent protesters

00:36:42.030 --> 00:36:46.470
for the right to vote,
revealing the injustice of it,

00:36:46.470 --> 00:36:48.660 position:56%
the changing broader public opinion.

00:36:48.660 --> 00:36:51.550
It was 50 years before Selma.

00:36:51.550 --> 00:36:54.320
And it took 5 more years.

00:36:54.320 --> 00:36:58.770
And a pioneering use of
strategies and tactics of protest

00:36:58.770 --> 00:37:02.990
that really began with the suffrage
movement in the United States.

00:37:02.990 --> 00:37:04.290
Everything from hunger strikes.

00:37:04.290 --> 00:37:07.190
They picketed the White House
for two years, straight.

00:37:07.190 --> 00:37:11.080
They ran political candidates
against Woodrow Wilson

00:37:11.080 --> 00:37:12.500
in states where they could.

00:37:12.500 --> 00:37:14.000
A whole host of things.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:18.200
All this before Gandhi used a
lot of these tactics in India.

00:37:18.200 --> 00:37:20.510
Certainly before the
sit down strikes

00:37:20.510 --> 00:37:22.800
and the American Labor
Movement in the '30s.

00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:25.330
And obviously before the
civil rights movements

00:37:25.330 --> 00:37:26.720
of the '50s and '60s.

00:37:26.720 --> 00:37:31.230
And finally, in 1920,
won the right to vote.

00:37:31.230 --> 00:37:32.900
And the electorate, the size

00:37:32.900 --> 00:37:36.090
of the electorate doubled
in one fell swoop.

00:37:36.090 --> 00:37:39.690
It was an extraordinary
breakthrough.

00:37:39.690 --> 00:37:47.360
Much of the 20th century, there was
this continued inexorable pressure,

00:37:47.360 --> 00:37:49.220
but there were a lot
of ongoing problems

00:37:49.220 --> 00:37:51.400
that built up, and built up.

00:37:51.400 --> 00:37:55.940
And the true ultimate breakthrough,
which I won't go into much detail

00:37:55.940 --> 00:37:58.670
about because it's something
you know the most about,

00:37:58.670 --> 00:38:03.980
came with the Voting Rights Act of
1965 when for the very first time,

00:38:03.980 --> 00:38:08.130
really, we as a country,
articulated the expectation

00:38:08.130 --> 00:38:10.810
that every eligible citizen
would be able to vote.

00:38:10.810 --> 00:38:12.480
And it as accompanied at the time

00:38:12.480 --> 00:38:15.080
by a constitutional
amendment ending the poll tax.

00:38:15.080 --> 00:38:19.300
By another constitutional amendment
lowering the voting age to 18.

00:38:19.300 --> 00:38:25.080
All I will say in terms of
the Voting Rights Act is

00:38:25.080 --> 00:38:30.590
that it too was the
product of political forces

00:38:30.590 --> 00:38:34.740
that were complex, and intense.

00:38:34.740 --> 00:38:39.350
And obviously the principle movers

00:38:39.350 --> 00:38:45.270
of that voting rights act were the
ordinary people who braved violence

00:38:45.270 --> 00:38:46.590
and even death in Selma,

00:38:46.590 --> 00:38:52.010
Alabama during the great voting
rights struggle and march there.

00:38:52.010 --> 00:38:54.130
But it's also the case
that it was the product

00:38:54.130 --> 00:38:58.270 position:56%
of this incredibly fascinating duel,

00:38:58.270 --> 00:39:02.830 position:56%
joust between these two viscerally
talented southern political leaders.

00:39:02.830 --> 00:39:06.530
Dr. Martin Luther King
and Lyndon Johnson.

00:39:06.530 --> 00:39:09.580 position:56%
And you know this is one of the
questions that arose after the movie

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:12.970
"Selma" was did Johnson, you
know did he get a fair treatment

00:39:12.970 --> 00:39:14.270
in that movie.

00:39:14.270 --> 00:39:18.250
And I certainly came out of the
research concluding no he did not.

00:39:18.250 --> 00:39:24.160 position:56%
Johnson was most of the time
strongly for and extremely important

00:39:24.160 --> 00:39:25.630
in the fight for voting rights.

00:39:25.630 --> 00:39:28.510
But King and Johnson pushed
and pulled with each other.

00:39:28.510 --> 00:39:31.270
And so much of their
interaction was taped.

00:39:31.270 --> 00:39:33.870
And so you can hear these
incredible conversations.

00:39:33.870 --> 00:39:38.830
Three days before Bloody
Sunday, the Friday before,

00:39:38.830 --> 00:39:41.320
King came to the White
House and met with Johnson.

00:39:41.320 --> 00:39:45.170
And Johnson did not tell
King, 'by the way Dr. King,

00:39:45.170 --> 00:39:48.580
I've ordered the Justice Department
to draft the Voting Rights Act'

00:39:48.580 --> 00:39:51.690
over the rejection of the
liberals who were there actually.

00:39:51.690 --> 00:39:54.050
'I've ordered them to draft
it and we've negotiated it

00:39:54.050 --> 00:39:56.760
with the Republicans
in the Senate already.'

00:39:56.760 --> 00:40:00.410
And King did not tell Johnson,
'by the way Mr. President,

00:40:00.410 --> 00:40:05.040
turn on your TV on Sunday,
we're marching in Selma.'

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:09.000
And the reaction of course,

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:13.110
to that public violence created a
spontaneous national mass movement

00:40:13.110 --> 00:40:16.830
demanding action that enabled
Johnson, both pushed Johnson

00:40:16.830 --> 00:40:20.280
and enabled him to then go before
the Congress a week later and give

00:40:20.280 --> 00:40:24.550 position:56%
that great speech where he said, 'we
shall overcome' embracing the slogan

00:40:24.550 --> 00:40:26.220
of the civil rights movement.

00:40:26.220 --> 00:40:27.750
And during this period, and after,

00:40:27.750 --> 00:40:32.280
American democracy achieved a
formal openness, a formal equality

00:40:32.280 --> 00:40:34.440
that it had never had before.

00:40:34.440 --> 00:40:37.050
And when I was going up, when
I was learning this stuff,

00:40:37.050 --> 00:40:38.680
that was sort of you
put your pencils down,

00:40:38.680 --> 00:40:40.510
that was the status quo.

00:40:40.510 --> 00:40:43.320
And that was the expectation.

00:40:43.320 --> 00:40:46.230
It was expected that these
issues were a thing of the past

00:40:46.230 --> 00:40:49.630
and that they weren't the subject
of intense current fighting.

00:40:49.630 --> 00:40:52.590
Well, that is not how
it's turned out.

00:40:52.590 --> 00:40:54.350
The last 15 years has seen,

00:40:54.350 --> 00:40:58.480
once again as we see throughout
American history, tremendous focus

00:40:58.480 --> 00:41:00.190
on these rules of democracy.

00:41:00.190 --> 00:41:02.240
And I think a lot of
it actually started

00:41:02.240 --> 00:41:05.640 position:56%
with the recount in Florida in 2000.

00:41:05.640 --> 00:41:08.170
Probably about 4 in the
morning that first night,

00:41:08.170 --> 00:41:11.610
when people realized the country
was really closely divided,

00:41:11.610 --> 00:41:14.350
that turnout now mattered a lot.

00:41:14.350 --> 00:41:18.290
That you could win an election
by manipulating the system

00:41:18.290 --> 00:41:22.270
or by turning your side out, or
by suppressing the other side.

00:41:22.270 --> 00:41:28.940
And you began to see as a
strategy, building overtime,

00:41:28.940 --> 00:41:32.890
a drive to restrict voting rights.

00:41:32.890 --> 00:41:37.890
And this is where I get to
the contemporary part where,

00:41:37.890 --> 00:41:43.630
I will note that as I said,
this is often a partisan fight.

00:41:43.630 --> 00:41:47.640
It's often been the Democrats who
have been the side of restricting

00:41:47.640 --> 00:41:48.940
or expanding the right to vote.

00:41:48.940 --> 00:41:51.210
It's often been Republicans
were the most for,

00:41:51.210 --> 00:41:52.630
for example woman's voting rights.

00:41:52.630 --> 00:41:54.610
Who have been on the
side of expanding

00:41:54.610 --> 00:41:56.590
or constricting the right to vote.

00:41:56.590 --> 00:41:59.780
Right now in America today it
is the Conservative Movement,

00:41:59.780 --> 00:42:02.640
and the Republican Party that
is pushing for these laws

00:42:02.640 --> 00:42:04.820
to make it harder for
people to vote.

00:42:04.820 --> 00:42:10.820
And the argument is made that this
is necessary to stop voter fraud.

00:42:10.820 --> 00:42:13.230
As the only kind of voter fraud

00:42:13.230 --> 00:42:18.040 position:56%
that these laws really address would
be in-person voter impersonation.

00:42:18.040 --> 00:42:20.830
Someone walking in and claiming
to be someone they're not.

00:42:20.830 --> 00:42:26.260
And every bit of research will
tell you that that is less likely

00:42:26.260 --> 00:42:29.760
that you are more likely to be hit
by lightning in the United States,

00:42:29.760 --> 00:42:33.110
statistically than to commit
in-person voter impersonation.

00:42:33.110 --> 00:42:40.360
Despite this concerted
strategic effort,

00:42:40.360 --> 00:42:42.930 position:56%
not a whole lot happened until 2011.

00:42:42.930 --> 00:42:48.810
In 2011, a lot of state
legislatures changed hands.

00:42:48.810 --> 00:42:52.840
And instantly you saw laws
being passed all over the place

00:42:52.840 --> 00:42:54.300
to make it harder to vote.

00:42:54.300 --> 00:42:58.550
Nineteen states passed 24 new
laws in a few months' time.

00:42:58.550 --> 00:43:02.120
They ranged from harsh and
restricted new forms of voter ID,

00:43:02.120 --> 00:43:04.750
to cutbacks in the early
voting, but especially

00:43:04.750 --> 00:43:06.940
on the days used by
African-Americans.

00:43:06.940 --> 00:43:08.640 position:56%
To ending election day registration,

00:43:08.640 --> 00:43:11.270
to crackdowns on voter
registration drives.

00:43:11.270 --> 00:43:13.160
A whole host of things.

00:43:13.160 --> 00:43:16.910
The Brennan Center, we played
a bit of a role in this,

00:43:16.910 --> 00:43:19.300
in that this was happening
in public, obviously,

00:43:19.300 --> 00:43:21.450
this was not a secret, it
was in state legislatures,

00:43:21.450 --> 00:43:23.570 position:56%
but the dots had not been connected.

00:43:23.570 --> 00:43:27.910
And a year before, in October
2011, we put out a report.

00:43:27.910 --> 00:43:30.910
We looked at all of
this stuff and concluded

00:43:30.910 --> 00:43:34.620
that 5 million people might have
the right to vote restricted

00:43:34.620 --> 00:43:37.390
or affected, or even lost.

00:43:37.390 --> 00:43:40.750
And that helped kickoff
a big national debate.

00:43:40.750 --> 00:43:44.420
It helped kickoff an awareness
on the part of a lot of people

00:43:44.420 --> 00:43:49.020
that this was a political
strategy being carried out.

00:43:49.020 --> 00:43:54.270 position:56%
And so that when we and other voting
rights groups went to court in 2012,

00:43:54.270 --> 00:43:58.050
the spring of 2012,
every single ones

00:43:58.050 --> 00:44:00.520
of the worst new laws
was blocked, or bunted,

00:44:00.520 --> 00:44:02.420
or postponed, or repealed.

00:44:02.420 --> 00:44:04.240
And it didn't matter if
it was Republican judge

00:44:04.240 --> 00:44:07.360
or a Democratic judge, or a
state judge, or a federal judge.

00:44:07.360 --> 00:44:10.200
They understood that there was
something fundamental and sacred

00:44:10.200 --> 00:44:14.030
in the right to vote that was
actually improperly being affected.

00:44:14.030 --> 00:44:15.870
And that was kind of where it stood

00:44:15.870 --> 00:44:18.500
until the Supreme Court
got involved.

00:44:18.500 --> 00:44:22.300
Which is a much more divided and
much more frankly partisan court

00:44:22.300 --> 00:44:25.020
than you find in most
other courthouses.

00:44:25.020 --> 00:44:28.030
And as you may know, in
2013, the Supreme Court

00:44:28.030 --> 00:44:32.360 position:56%
in a case called Shelby County
versus Holder, struck down the heart

00:44:32.360 --> 00:44:34.620
of the Voting Rights Act of 1965,

00:44:34.620 --> 00:44:37.380 position:56%
which everybody acknowledged was
the most successful civil rights law

00:44:37.380 --> 00:44:38.770
in American history.

00:44:38.770 --> 00:44:42.380
This was the part of the law that
required states with a history

00:44:42.380 --> 00:44:46.410
of discrimination in voting to get
voting changes cleared in advanced

00:44:46.410 --> 00:44:49.040
by the Justice Department
or a federal court.

00:44:49.040 --> 00:44:55.810
And this was the ruling
during the arguments,

00:44:55.810 --> 00:44:59.070
across the street, down the block.

00:44:59.070 --> 00:45:02.350
This was the case where Justice
Scalia said in the courtroom

00:45:02.350 --> 00:45:05.240
that he thought that the voting
rights act was nothing more than,

00:45:05.240 --> 00:45:08.530
as he put it, a racial entitlement

00:45:08.530 --> 00:45:11.730
which actually elicited
gasps in the courtroom.

00:45:11.730 --> 00:45:13.030
He didn't write the opinion.

00:45:13.030 --> 00:45:15.660
Chief Justice Roberts
wrote the opinion.

00:45:15.660 --> 00:45:19.100
And he made a point
which has some validity.

00:45:19.100 --> 00:45:20.470
He said you know,

00:45:20.470 --> 00:45:25.130
voter participation rates among
African-Americans in many places,

00:45:25.130 --> 00:45:28.360
including the South are now
higher than among white voters.

00:45:28.360 --> 00:45:31.900
His main argument in effect
was that was then, this is now.

00:45:31.900 --> 00:45:34.260 position:56%
Therefore, it's not needed any more.

00:45:34.260 --> 00:45:38.800
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg wrote
a famous dissent in that case.

00:45:38.800 --> 00:45:43.440
She said that that's like standing
in a rainstorm holding an umbrella

00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:46.420
and not getting wet,
and deciding therefore

00:45:46.420 --> 00:45:49.110
that you can throw
away the umbrella.

00:45:49.110 --> 00:45:50.650
So who was right?

00:45:50.650 --> 00:45:55.420
Who was right as a predicted
matter of what would happen?

00:45:55.420 --> 00:46:00.540
Two hours after the
ruling came down,

00:46:00.540 --> 00:46:03.710
The State of Texas
implemented its voter ID law,

00:46:03.710 --> 00:46:07.280
and I should say I'm
actually for voter ID.

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:10.360 position:56%
I'm not against voter ID, I think it
makes sense for people to have to be

00:46:10.360 --> 00:46:14.130
who they say they are and it's not
crazy to ask t hem to prove it.

00:46:14.130 --> 00:46:18.860
I'm against requiring forms of ID
that lots of people don't have.

00:46:18.860 --> 00:46:22.760 position:56%
Nationwide, around 11% of eligible
voters don't have a driver's license

00:46:22.760 --> 00:46:25.020
or the other kind of
ID that's required.

00:46:25.020 --> 00:46:29.490
In Texas, two hours later
the law was implemented,

00:46:29.490 --> 00:46:32.430
it's the harshest law
in the country.

00:46:32.430 --> 00:46:33.730
It's kind of notorious.

00:46:33.730 --> 00:46:36.730
It's the one where you cannot
use your University of Texas ID

00:46:36.730 --> 00:46:41.350
as a government ID, but you can use
your conceal to carry gun permit.

00:46:41.350 --> 00:46:44.030
And the, now Stephen Colbert said,

00:46:44.030 --> 00:46:45.330
well that's actually
very democratic.

00:46:45.330 --> 00:46:49.100
It's a lot easier to get a
gun than a college education.

00:46:49.100 --> 00:46:52.270
But he partisan intent
was fairly naked.

00:46:52.270 --> 00:46:56.450 position:56%
And at that precise moment, two
hours after the Supreme Court ruled,

00:46:56.450 --> 00:47:00.940
608,000 registered voters in
Texas lost their right to vote.

00:47:00.940 --> 00:47:03.350
Not potential, maybe
they'd vote someday.

00:47:03.350 --> 00:47:05.290
Registered voters.

00:47:05.290 --> 00:47:07.300 position:56%
Disproportionately African-American.

00:47:07.300 --> 00:47:09.020
Disproportionately Latino.

00:47:09.020 --> 00:47:11.160
Disproportionately poor.

00:47:11.160 --> 00:47:14.760
Disproportionately either
the elderly, or the young.

00:47:14.760 --> 00:47:22.570 position:56%
And one of those voters was a woman
who we met named Sandy Louise Bates.

00:47:22.570 --> 00:47:25.000 position:56%
We and others went to court on this.

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:26.860
And we met Sandy Louise Bates.

00:47:26.860 --> 00:47:30.350
And she was born in Mississippi.

00:47:30.350 --> 00:47:32.300
She remembered counting out money

00:47:32.300 --> 00:47:35.840
for her grandmother
to pay the poll tax.

00:47:35.840 --> 00:47:38.670
She moved to Detroit and Chicago.

00:47:38.670 --> 00:47:41.090 position:56%
Sort of the classic great migration.

00:47:41.090 --> 00:47:43.820
She actually went to college.

00:47:43.820 --> 00:47:45.120
She worked.

00:47:45.120 --> 00:47:47.870
Then she retired, and she moved
to Texas, Round Rock, Texas,

00:47:47.870 --> 00:47:51.940
where she lives on Social
Security and nothing else.

00:47:51.940 --> 00:47:55.310
She's been voting since
she was 21 years old.

00:47:55.310 --> 00:47:58.160
And she lost the right to vote.

00:47:58.160 --> 00:48:03.470
And we asked her, why didn't you
just get your birth certificate

00:48:03.470 --> 00:48:04.770
from Mississippi.

00:48:04.770 --> 00:48:06.070
Why didn't you go through
the process

00:48:06.070 --> 00:48:08.200
and get your birth
certificate from Mississippi?

00:48:08.200 --> 00:48:14.390
And she said well that costs
$42 and I had to put those $42

00:48:14.390 --> 00:48:16.390
where they would be the most good.

00:48:16.390 --> 00:48:19.550
You can't eat a birth certificate.

00:48:19.550 --> 00:48:23.590
And she was the lead
witness in the federal trial,

00:48:23.590 --> 00:48:28.260 position:56%
and with many others persuaded the
federal judge to strike down the law

00:48:28.260 --> 00:48:32.310
as discriminatory, illegal,
violating the remaining parts

00:48:32.310 --> 00:48:35.160
of the Voting Rights Act
and the Constitution.

00:48:35.160 --> 00:48:40.710
That ruling was upheld by the most
conservative federal appeals court

00:48:40.710 --> 00:48:42.130
in the country.

00:48:42.130 --> 00:48:43.640
The Fifth Circuit.

00:48:43.640 --> 00:48:44.940
And the law's still on the books.

00:48:44.940 --> 00:48:46.240
It's still in effect.

00:48:46.240 --> 00:48:47.540
It's going to be in
effect in November.

00:48:47.540 --> 00:48:56.240
Because the simplified answer is
Texas is appealing very slowly.

00:48:56.240 --> 00:49:00.030
And the wheels of justice
are grinding very slowly.

00:49:00.030 --> 00:49:03.010
And ultimately this is not a fight
that will be won in the court

00:49:03.010 --> 00:49:05.980
of law, but in the
court of public opinion.

00:49:05.980 --> 00:49:11.710
And so we have every reason to
expect a lot of hand to hand combat

00:49:11.710 --> 00:49:13.810
in courtrooms all over the country.

00:49:13.810 --> 00:49:16.840
A lot of drives to make it
possible for people to vote.

00:49:16.840 --> 00:49:20.750
We think that these new laws
will affect polling places,

00:49:20.750 --> 00:49:22.620
certainly where we've
seen already evidence

00:49:22.620 --> 00:49:26.180
that they cause long
lines and chaos.

00:49:26.180 --> 00:49:27.710
And there's reason to be worried.

00:49:27.710 --> 00:49:31.740
But there is also, I'll say in
conclusion reason for optimism.

00:49:31.740 --> 00:49:33.130
Why would there be optimism,

00:49:33.130 --> 00:49:36.290
other than temperament why
would there be optimism?

00:49:36.290 --> 00:49:43.320
Just as perhaps we say in
the early 20th century,

00:49:43.320 --> 00:49:47.790
this focus on the rules of
democracy, this recognition

00:49:47.790 --> 00:49:51.210
that some people are trying to
take away others' right to vote.

00:49:51.210 --> 00:49:54.210
This recognition that the system
needs to be changed if we want

00:49:54.210 --> 00:49:58.680
to solve our problems, is creating
its own moment of pushback,

00:49:58.680 --> 00:50:00.160
of renewal one hopes

00:50:00.160 --> 00:50:02.340
of revitalization of
these institutions.

00:50:02.340 --> 00:50:05.870
There's actually a tremendous
ferment going on on the issues

00:50:05.870 --> 00:50:08.460
of democracy all over the country.

00:50:08.460 --> 00:50:11.650
Plainly we see this in the
election, in both parties.

00:50:11.650 --> 00:50:16.660
Where weather it's Bernie Sanders
saying he's winning these primaries

00:50:16.660 --> 00:50:20.770
because of his position on campaign
finance, or Donald Trump saying

00:50:20.770 --> 00:50:22.660
that he's the only one
who can't be bought.

00:50:22.660 --> 00:50:24.890
Or Hillary Clinton
putting out what I regard

00:50:24.890 --> 00:50:29.040
as by far the most robust set
of policy reform proposals

00:50:29.040 --> 00:50:32.920
on this stuff, all though she
talks about it in a more muted way.

00:50:32.920 --> 00:50:35.400
This issue is at the
center of debate again.

00:50:35.400 --> 00:50:39.060 position:56%
And you're seeing breakthroughs on
these issues all across the country.

00:50:39.060 --> 00:50:42.790
The single biggest change that
could make a big difference

00:50:42.790 --> 00:50:46.460
in our voting right now, would be

00:50:46.460 --> 00:50:49.700
to change the way we register
voters in the United States.

00:50:49.700 --> 00:50:52.510
If we move to automatic
voter registration.

00:50:52.510 --> 00:50:54.200
Automatic and universal
registration,

00:50:54.200 --> 00:50:58.470
which is how every
other democracy does it.

00:50:58.470 --> 00:51:00.950
If we made it so that if
you're eligible to vote,

00:51:00.950 --> 00:51:03.320
the government has the list, it's
responsible for keeping the list

00:51:03.320 --> 00:51:04.790
and you stay on the list.

00:51:04.790 --> 00:51:07.520
It would add 50 million
people to the rolls,

00:51:07.520 --> 00:51:10.090
permanently, would cost less.

00:51:10.090 --> 00:51:19.050 position:56%
And for people who are worried about
fraud, it would address the accuracy

00:51:19.050 --> 00:51:21.360
of the list, it would
clean up the lists

00:51:21.360 --> 00:51:24.260
and it would make it
harder to abuse.

00:51:24.260 --> 00:51:26.260
And the exciting thing
is it's starting

00:51:26.260 --> 00:51:27.660
to happen all over the country.

00:51:27.660 --> 00:51:33.820
In the last year and a half,
Oregon, California, West Virginia,

00:51:33.820 --> 00:51:38.600
by bipartisan vote, Vermont,
by tri-partisan vote.

00:51:38.600 --> 00:51:41.150
They've got the Democrats and
Republicans and the Socialists all

00:51:41.150 --> 00:51:45.480
to vote for it, enacted automatic
voter registration for people

00:51:45.480 --> 00:51:48.530
who interact with the DMV in those
states and they can broaden it

00:51:48.530 --> 00:51:49.830
out to other agencies too.

00:51:49.830 --> 00:51:53.380
We had a conference a couple
weeks ago and the State

00:51:53.380 --> 00:51:55.470
of Connecticut came and announced

00:51:55.470 --> 00:51:58.060
that the night before they
decided they were going to do it

00:51:58.060 --> 00:52:00.420
without even waiting
for the legislature.

00:52:00.420 --> 00:52:03.470
The Illinois legislature,
last week passed this.

00:52:03.470 --> 00:52:06.060
While we don't know if Governor
Rauner is going to sign it,

00:52:06.060 --> 00:52:08.260
there are enough votes
to override a veto.

00:52:08.260 --> 00:52:12.990 position:56%
We expect that if that happens, then
1 out of 5 voters will now be living

00:52:12.990 --> 00:52:14.980
in states with automatic
registration.

00:52:14.980 --> 00:52:17.960 position:56%
We know from Oregon that it has
tripled the registration rates month

00:52:17.960 --> 00:52:19.260
by month there.

00:52:19.260 --> 00:52:20.560
It would be a tremendous
breakthrough

00:52:20.560 --> 00:52:22.440
and it's happening
all over the country.

00:52:22.440 --> 00:52:24.970
There are things like
that that are happening.

00:52:24.970 --> 00:52:27.710
Creative new versions of
public financing being enacted

00:52:27.710 --> 00:52:29.630
for campaign finance.

00:52:29.630 --> 00:52:33.430
Redistricting reform, such
as redistricting commissions.

00:52:33.430 --> 00:52:36.740
Being approved up by the
Supreme Court last year

00:52:36.740 --> 00:52:38.040
and pushed in states.

00:52:38.040 --> 00:52:40.630
Whether it was Ohio where
Governor Kasich backed it,

00:52:40.630 --> 00:52:42.980
or California where
Governor Schwarzenegger,

00:52:42.980 --> 00:52:45.180
or Florida where it
was liberal democrats

00:52:45.180 --> 00:52:46.580 position:56%
who pushed the redistricting reform.

00:52:46.580 --> 00:52:47.950
It's sort of both parties
[inaudible]

00:52:47.950 --> 00:52:52.010
and the reform is actually
genuinely bipartisan as a result.

00:52:52.010 --> 00:52:53.730
There is a lot happening.

00:52:53.730 --> 00:52:55.830
So that's really the question.

00:52:55.830 --> 00:52:58.180
We are on the knife's edge.

00:52:58.180 --> 00:53:01.210
We could be in a period
like the late 19th century.

00:53:01.210 --> 00:53:02.510
The signs are there.

00:53:02.510 --> 00:53:03.920
Where our democracy
slides backwards,

00:53:03.920 --> 00:53:06.580
where participation
recedes, where the right

00:53:06.580 --> 00:53:08.560
to vote takes on less meaning.

00:53:08.560 --> 00:53:12.460
Or, as I hope and believe is
more likely to be the case,

00:53:12.460 --> 00:53:16.260
we could be in a period, like
what followed, a time of renewal,

00:53:16.260 --> 00:53:18.540
of activism on these issues,

00:53:18.540 --> 00:53:22.380
that helps create a new
moment for American democracy.

00:53:22.380 --> 00:53:25.880
Ultimately, even if this
happens it won't be over.

00:53:25.880 --> 00:53:30.420
John Adams was right there
will be no end of it.

00:53:30.420 --> 00:53:32.650
There will never be a point
where we're not fighting

00:53:32.650 --> 00:53:34.980
over what it means
to have a democracy.

00:53:34.980 --> 00:53:37.440
But the next chapter will
be written by all of us,

00:53:37.440 --> 00:53:40.510
and those who come after, so.

