01:00:08.650 --> 01:00:12.910
And actually is it explicitly
authorized in the 14th amendment

01:00:12.910 --> 01:00:18.310
to the Constitution where it says
states cannot restrict the right

01:00:18.310 --> 01:00:22.310
to vote, except for somebody who's
committed a felony or rebellion.

01:00:22.310 --> 01:00:26.000
So there is a long
constitutional provenance

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:28.230
to felony disenfranchisement.

01:00:28.230 --> 01:00:35.700
However, the way the system
exists is unquestionably unfair,

01:00:35.700 --> 01:00:38.050
far harsher than other
countries have it,

01:00:38.050 --> 01:00:40.860
and with a very significant
racial impact.

01:00:40.860 --> 01:00:43.100
A lot of these laws
are actually passed

01:00:43.100 --> 01:00:46.960
or created the way they were
created during the Jim Crow Era.

01:00:46.960 --> 01:00:51.290 position:56%
And one of the positive developments
this happened, it's not so much

01:00:51.290 --> 01:00:53.620
about voting by people in prison.

01:00:53.620 --> 01:00:57.770
But what about the millions and
millions of our fellow Americans

01:00:57.770 --> 01:01:00.720
who have been in prison,
or who have been part

01:01:00.720 --> 01:01:02.250
of the criminal justice system.

01:01:02.250 --> 01:01:04.270 position:56%
People with past felony convictions.

01:01:04.270 --> 01:01:08.340
And that's something where
